data.label:
Narrator

I took a look around. After my order to purge the general staff, I couldn't recognise many of the faces. These generals were certainly younger than their predecessors.

Narrator

Iosef stood up and picked up an extendable pointer from a shelf on the wall.

Iosef Lancea

"The Rumburgian troop movements in the last 24 hours indicate that they are bolstering their frontline strength."

Narrator

As Iosef was speaking, assistants handed out small booklets detailing the operation.

Rumburg Defence Questions Hub

Rumburg Defence Questions Hub

Player

"Give it to me straight. What are the odds of success?"

Narrator

There was a collective gasp from some of the generals' assistants.

Iosef Lancea

"The estimates put their active military personnel at around 900,000 to one million. Meanwhile, we have approximately 600,000 soldiers on the ground."

Iosef Lancea

"Rumburg doesn't have any idea what or who they are dealing with."

Narrator

Some of the generals laughed.

Player

"To say that I am worried would be an understatement."

Iosef Lancea

"We will destroy their armies and send them back to whatever hellhole they came from."

Valken Kruger

"But soldiers with faith do, Iosef."

Iosef Lancea

"Good. Now we have to talk about our defensive strategy."

Iosef Lancea

"Rest assured, Mr. President. I am more than confident that we will win."

Iosef Lancea

"Our fleet currently totals up to 60 ships and approximately 60,000 sailors."

Iosef Lancea

"I predict that they will try to block our seaports, reducing our trade and disrupting our supplies."

Iosef Lancea

"Regardless, they are prepared to fight and die for their country, Mr. President."

Iosef Lancea

"Unfortunately our combat readiness has been getting worse and worse over the years. That's because we did not allocate enough budget to hold proper drills."

Iosef Lancea

"Due to the potential of an invasion, all three armies have been undergoing rigorous drills, especially during the past few months."

Iosef Lancea

"They are prepared to fight and die for their country, Mr. President."

Iosef Lancea

"No need for flattery. Just doing our duty."

Iosef Lancea

"But no worries, Mr. President. I'm sure he will be fine."

Iosef Lancea

"Regardless, they are prepared to fight and die for their country, Mr. President."

Iosef Lancea

"The Sordland military code is clear. He will serve his country just like everyone else."

Player

"Pull him back to Holsord immediately. That's an order."

Player

"I'm getting more and more worried."

Player

"Thank you for letting me know, Iosef."

Iosef Lancea

"I'm afraid I can't do that. Even if it's an order from you."

Iosef Lancea

"Now, let's start discussing our path to victory in this war."

Valken Kruger

"Our top strategic location is Thornbourgh."

Player

"What if she flees Thornbourgh before we get there?"

Iosef Lancea

"Other than that, we do have allies that could aid us but I see no point."

Iosef Lancea

"At any rate, this is what we are dealing with."

Iosef Lancea

"I will be frank. We can't fend them off alone. We need help."

Player

"Very well. Call our allies to the war."

Player

"No. We don't need anyone else to defend our borders."

Iosef Lancea

"We are now a full member of CSP and they will join us in the war, which will be of tremendous support."

Iosef Lancea

"You tasked us with the defense of this nation, and we will defend our nation."

Iosef Lancea

"Your confidence is inspiring, Mr. President."

Iosef Lancea

"We have begun communications already. Now we can make it official."

Iosef Lancea

"Here is the hard truth."

Player

"Very well. I will trust your judgement."

Iosef Lancea

"Mr. President. I have a duty to this nation to protect it from its enemies."

Iosef Lancea

"Even if that means defying you."

Player

"It is our war to fight. We will not depend on others."

Valken Kruger

"Sordland will stand alone as always."

Player

"Very well. We don't need anyone else to defend our borders."

Player

"We can't risk anything. Call our allies to the war."

Player

"Maybe we should've tried to get some allies after all."

Player

"Sordland has always been alone, Iosef."

Player

"Very well. I will trust your judgement then."

Valken Kruger

"We do have allies that could aid us, but I see no point."

Player

"I said I don't want to take any risks. We will call our allies."

Valken Kruger

"We can fend them off easily."

Player

"He's not authorized to join this meeting. Let's proceed."

Player

"So you're not retiring after all?"

Deivid Wisci

"Anton, please allow me to assist in the war plans."

Narrator

Deivid stood there and stared at me for a moment.

Valken Kruger

"Precisely! We cannot place our republic in the hands of foreign interests."

Player

"What allies? You've gone to all this trouble for nothing, Deivid."

Player

"Allies? Who needs them? We have full trust in our capacity to win this war by ourselves."

Player

"You might be right about that."

Player

"You're afraid that they might backstab us?"

Deivid Wisci

"I'm sure that our allies will agree to fight by our side."

Iosef Lancea

"Glad you've finally come to your senses, Mr. President."

Player

"First you beg me to call them in, now you're suspicious of them?"

Deivid Wisci

"However, depending on our plans and our past interactions with them, some may be more committed than others."

Deivid Wisci

"I assure you I am, Mr. President. But your term has not ended yet, and you could clearly still use my guidance."

Iosef Lancea

"Let us move on to our war strategy."

Iosef Lancea

"Our first objective is taking Tzarsbourgh."

Player

"I thought Rumburg was hard to invade."

Player

"Can't we just defend our border?"

Player

"So how are we taking this city?"

Iosef Lancea

"Unfortunately, Mr. President, simple defense is not a possibility."

Valken Kruger

"Entering a war of attrition without dealing a killing blow to Rumburg will place us in a disastrous position."

Valken Kruger

"They will simply wear us out with their larger military and superior technology."

Iosef Lancea

"If we only defend, the world will see this war as a stalemate."

Valken Kruger

"If we only defend, the world will see this war as a stalemate."

Iosef Lancea

"With the CSP looming on the horizon, looking for an excuse to intervene..."

Iosef Lancea

"Especially when we have CSP on our side."

Iosef Lancea

"With the CSP looming on the horizon, looking for an excuse to intervene..."

Iosef Lancea

"However, if we take two of their key cities, we might be able to turn the tide on them."

Player

"The best defense is certainly a good offense."

Narrator

I heard the sound of boots running down the hall. A soldier rushed in, urgently pulled Valken aside and whispered in his ear.

Player

"Another general? I thought everyone was here."

Player

"It is indeed an honor, sir."

Player

"Got bored of your gardening, old man?"

Tarquin Soll

"There is no greater honor than to protect one's nation, Mr. President."

Tarquin Soll

"I'm here to show you how to win this war, son."

Narrator

Soll gave a satisfactory nod.

Valken Kruger

"I don't think the Colonel's war credentials need to be reiterated."

Player

"He has no right to be here."

Player

"You've meddled in my business for the last time. Guards!"

Tarquin Soll

"Not yet, my boy. Shall we get started?"

Valken Kruger

"One is to simply dig in and endure their first wave of attack, then retaliate after they are weakened."

Valken Kruger

"Our second option is to launch a full-scale offensive on Tzarsbourgh. We will strike at them hard and fast before they have the chance to draw first blood."

Iosef Lancea

"Which is insane in my opinion."

Iosef Lancea

"Our second option is to do a pincer attack to wipe out their forces and then march toward Tzarsbourgh."

Player

"How is digging in and waiting for them to attack a good option?"

Player

"Why can't we just launch an assault on Tzarsbourgh?"

Player

"Tell me more about the pincer attack."

Valken Kruger

"The border fortifications we built are for this very purpose."

Valken Kruger

"The expansion of our land forces will serve to fill any gap we have in our border."

Valken Kruger

"They outnumbered us, Iosef. With this move we will destroy or, at worst, limit the effectiveness of their advantage."

Iosef Lancea

"There are two options on the table at the moment."

Iosef Lancea

"Our third option is to do a pincer attack to wipe out their forces, then march toward Tzarsbourgh."

Iosef Lancea

"They are untrained soldiers with little experience. We cannot rely on them to hold the line for long."

Tarquin Soll

"The expansion of our land forces will serve to fill any gap we have in our border."

Iosef Lancea

"Unfortunately, we have to choose wisely. Our troops' combat readiness is at an all-time low. It will take them some time on the battlefield to regain their sharpness."

BaseGame.Rumburg_AlliesCalledToWar == true && BaseGameIsolated.Turn10_SnO_Phase1Plan_AlliancesBriefing == false && \n(BaseGame.Joined_ATO == false && BaseGame.Joined_CSP == false)

nan

Player

"I'm ready to choose our first move."

Iosef Lancea

"Whichever strategy we choose, our major allies will cover our flaws. We don't have to worry about our army's weaknesses."

Iosef Lancea

"Then our tanks will come in and puncture their defense at Crimsrad, followed up by our soldiers."

Iosef Lancea

"Let me remind you that we are butting heads with an army far larger than ours."

Valken Kruger

"You are forgetting that we will have the element of surprise."

Valken Kruger

"With our expanded air fleet, we can launch a carpet of bomb strikes on them."

Iosef Lancea

"General Kruger, I want to remind that you were against modernizing our air force at first. Now you see its benefits."

Valken Kruger

"I simply use the tools I have, Iosef. As any good general would."

Iosef Lancea

"They are a police force, Valken. Their skills will certainly be of use during the war, but they shouldn't join the front line as common soldiers."

Valken Kruger

"The gendarmerie can be deployed on the mainline as well to support the war effort."

Iosef Lancea

"Casualties are expected to a certain extent, so that Rumburg does not become suspicious of our real intentions. When they believe they are winning, they will push for Estord."

Iosef Lancea

"Our modernized army is trained and equipped for such a task."

Iosef Lancea

"I am confident that we will achieve complete victory with my strategy."

Iosef Lancea

"That is why I advised us to remove mandatory conscription."

Player

"Why don't we have the generals let them in on the strategy?"

Iosef Lancea

"And jeopardize the whole plan by having it leak to Rumburg's spies?"

Tarquin Soll

"I would suggest that we do not strike Tzarsbourgh right away."

Tarquin Soll

"However unreliable our allies can be, they can cover our military weaknesses. if we utilize our cooperation well."

Tarquin Soll

"Doubling down on defense and grinding down the enemy's forces has some merit to it."

Tarquin Soll

"I don't see a path to victory by ourselves."

Player

"Let us dig down and invite them to certain death."

Player

"We will show them what we're made of. Let us march toward Tzarsbourgh."

Iosef Lancea

"The decision is already made, Valken."

Iosef Lancea

"After all my explanations, this is the path you choose?"

Iosef Lancea

"On to our allies then."

Player

"Have them go through Lards and Merdon to flank the Rumburg army from the east."

Player

"No, have them assist us in the pincer attack."

Player

"Yes, I trust that they will be able to take Dome."

Iosef Lancea

"Meanwhile, Agnolia would be assaulting Dome, creating a second front."

Iosef Lancea

"Lespia's armies will reinforce us on the front line."

Iosef Lancea

"Should we ask Valgsland to assist us in Agnland?"

Player

"No, Their armies would be more useful drawing Rumburg away."

Iosef Lancea

"So. Let's assume that at this point, we have Tzarsbourgh in our hands."

Player

"Why can't we just defend Tzarsbourgh from this point on?"

Iosef Lancea

"After Tzarsbourgh is taken, the enemy will be in shock and their morale will be low."

Iosef Lancea

"However, if we hesitate for even a moment, this window will close. Even worse, the enemy will realize that we are overextending and will try to cut us off. This will leave the bulk of our army isolated in the cold north."

Iosef Lancea

"Fortunately, our modernized forces have been properly trained and prepared for exactly such a mission."

Iosef Lancea

"Our gendarmerie can stay behind in Tzarsbourgh to cover our flank."

Valken Kruger

"As much as I want to crush all Rumburgian hope by taking their capital, our doctrine does not include these kinds of rapid advances."

Valken Kruger

"To boot, our supply line will be stretched too thin, creating a weak point that can be exploited by the enemy."

nan

Iosef Lancea

"We can either have them stay and defend our flank in Tzarsbourgh or assault Dome."

Deivid Wisci

"On that note, I would like to advise against having the Wehlen army fight together with our other allies."

Iosef Lancea

"That is out of the question, Mr. President"

Valken Kruger

"It will leave us out in the open and susceptible to a Rumburg pincer attack."

Iosef Lancea

"Just like the L-1 between Lachaven and Holsord."

Valken Kruger

"This will aid us in transporting military supplies and troops."

Valken Kruger

"You are overestimating their capabilities, Iosef. Our vast armed forces will quickly overwhelm them."

Valken Kruger

"We can easily launch an assault on Dome within half a week after taking Tzarsbourgh."

Iosef Lancea

"If they can withstand our assault, they can launch a counter-offensive with ease from the direction of Dome to retake Tzarsbourgh."

Valken Kruger

"The gendarmerie can stay behind and protect our flank from Tzarsbourgh."

Valken Kruger

"The reservists can be deployed in Tzarsbourgh to help with the defenses."

Iosef Lancea

"With Valgsland executing a naval invasion from the north, we can create another pincer movement, this time right at their capital."

Iosef Lancea

"Otherwise the invasion from the north will still continue splitting Rumburg's attention and troops."

Deivid Wisci

"Our industrial production and trade lanes will be crucial at that point in the war."

Iosef Lancea

"Our military industrial output is at the highest it's ever been. We won't have a problem providing our armed forces with what they need."

Iosef Lancea

"Three cheers for the Sordish military industrial complex."

Iosef Lancea

"Our military production is at an all-time low right now. We lack supplies in some units."

Tarquin Soll

"Without sufficient production capacity or supplies to be procured through trade, our chances at victory seem slim."

Tarquin Soll

"What have you done to Sordland, Rayne?"

Tarquin Soll

"Our chances certainly seem high. You've done well for our military, Rayne."

Tarquin Soll

"Luckily, we have a defense in depth strategy thanks to our reinforcement armies. Whichever strategy we choose, we will have some room to manouver."

Player

"We will attack Dome and lay out a defensive line. Let them come and get us."

Iosef Lancea

"If by some luck we succeed, it would be too late to attack Thornbourgh from Dome."

Valken Kruger

"However, with the capture of Dome, there will be no need to take Thornbourgh."

Valken Kruger

"However, with two of their largest cities in our hand, we can lay out a defensive line."

Iosef Lancea

"I'm adding it to our battle plan."

Iosef Lancea

"Now, let us decide on our allies' movements during this phase."

Iosef Lancea

"What should the Wehlen army do?"

Player

"Have them stay in Tzarsbourgh to cover our back."

Player

"Lespia can surely take Dome within a week. Let's coordinate with them on that."

Iosef Lancea

"Agnolia will probably try to assault Dome after they have finished assisting us in the pincer attack."

Iosef Lancea

"At this point, Valgsland will already have created a foothold at the north-eastern coast of Rumburg."

Iosef Lancea

"Since the Valgsland army would be poised to act, where should we send them next?"

Player

"Valgsland can surely take Dome within a week."

Player

"Let's have them guard our flanks."

Iosef Lancea

"And that, gentlemen, is our plan against Rumburg."

Narrator

Iosef handed me the order and waited for me to sign the document.

Narrator

He turned to the generals in the room.

Narrator

Valken turned to the generals in the room.

Valken Kruger

"We have work to do. Get back to your posts immediately."

Iosef Lancea

"We have work to do. Get back to your posts immediately."

Iosef Lancea

"Mr. President. We will need your executive order to mobilize the forces."

Iosef Lancea

"If we falter at any point during this war, it will be the end of Sordland as we know it."

Narrator

Only three people were left in the room. Me, Deivid and the Colonel.

Deivid Wisci

"Win or lose, this will be my last great contribution to my country."

Player

"That is our job, and we will succeed."

Narrator

The Colonel and I turned to face each other.

Player

"Thank you, Colonel. For being here."

Player

"When will you trust me to lead on my own, Colonel?"

Player

"Well? Did I make you proud?"

Tarquin Soll

"Where else would I be? A good leader is always there for his country in times of need."

Tarquin Soll

"Let's hope that the next time we meet, it will be under a Sordish Flag in Tzarsbourgh."

Player

"Ha. When we win, I will personally invite you to supper in Thornbourgh."
